Here's a JavaScript function that takes an array of 5 numbers and checks if any of them are prime. If a number is prime, it prints that number to the console:

```javascript
function printPrimeNumbers(numbers) {
  if (numbers.length !== 5) {
    console.error('The array must contain exactly 5 numbers');
    return;
  }

  function isPrime(num) {
    if (num <= 1) return false;
    if (num === 2) return true;
    if (num % 2 === 0) return false;
    for (let i = 3; i <= Math.sqrt(num); i += 2) {
      if (num % i === 0) return false;
    }
    return true;
  }

  numbers.forEach((number) => {
    if (isPrime(number)) {
      console.log(number);
    }
  });
}

// Example usage:
printPrimeNumbers([3, 4, 5, 6, 7]);
```

This function first checks if the input array has exactly 5 elements. Then it defines a helper function `isPrime` to determine if a given number is prime. After that, it iterates through the array and uses `isPrime` to check each number, printing it to the console if it is a prime number.

